WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.480
This is what an IDE is and why it makes your life way easier as a beginner.

00:00:03.480 --> 00:00:06.880
If you're just getting started with Python, data science, or building literally anything

00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:10.760
with code, you've probably just heard people say, open up your IDE, and you're like, what

00:00:10.760 --> 00:00:11.760
is that?

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:12.760
So let's break it down.

00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:16.040
IDE stands for Integrated Development Environment, and it's exactly what it sounds like.

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:19.400
It's a tool that gives you everything you need to write, run, and debug code all in

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:20.400
one place.

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:23.620
Basically, the difference between writing a novel in Microsoft Word versus Notepad.

00:00:23.620 --> 00:00:27.600
You can write code in a plain text editor, but with an IDE, you get syntax highlighting

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:31.920
so your code is color-coded and way easier to read, you get autocomplete, error detections,

00:00:31.920 --> 00:00:35.279
and a built-in terminal or console so you can run your code directly inside the app,

00:00:35.279 --> 00:00:38.880
and sometimes even visual tools and debuggers to help you get through code line by line.

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:43.200
Some popular IDEs are VS Code, which is good for everything, Python, WebDev, AI, you name

00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:46.520
it, JupyterLab, which is great for data science and machine learning notebooks, Positron,

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:50.040
which is my go-to for Python dashboards and data apps, especially if you want to see some

00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:54.240
of those visuals, and PyCharm, which is more advanced, but awesome for pure Python projects.

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:55.240
So how do you pick one?

00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:59.560
Honestly, if you start with VS Code, Jupyter Notebook, or Positron, they're all free, beginner-friendly,

00:00:59.560 --> 00:01:00.560
and well-supported.

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:03.200
As your projects grow and get more complex, you'll naturally figure out what tools feel

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:04.199
best for your workflow.

00:01:04.199 --> 00:01:07.040
Make sure to leave any questions in the comments below, and follow along for more data science

00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:08.040
content.

